<title type="html"><![CDATA[Getting homebrew news into a reliable source]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6454&amp;p=62326#p62326"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br /><div class="quotetitle">UncleSporky wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Even so, I do think it's a necessary policy, given the nature of free editing on a wiki.  How else could they dispute incorrect information?  I could claim to be the White House cook and I know for a fact that Obama's marriage is falling apart.  As original research, who could dispute this?<br /></div><br />I understand <em>why</em> Wikipedia has this policy. But if I have a debunking, how do I attract the attention of the mainstream media?</div><br />NBC Nightly News isn't the only accepted source.  Submit it to a related peer-reviewed journal.  If it's not relevant or important enough to fit in a journal, put it up on a blog, since gaming blogs seem to be considered legitimate sources.  Or simply leave it unsourced if it's not top-tier, policed information.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=3438">UncleSporky</a> — Thu Jun 03, 2010 10:03 am</p><hr />
